-- cell-zero-autopour: metacircular evaluator via autopour
--
-- This is what cell-zero-eval SHOULD look like once autopour exists.
-- No SQL escape hatch. No reaching below the abstraction. The cell
-- language expressing its own evaluation using only cell primitives.
--
-- Compare with cell-zero-eval.cell which achieves the same thing
-- by manipulating Dolt tables directly via SQL. That version proves
-- the runtime works. This version proves the LANGUAGE is expressive.
--
-- Requires two new primitives (not yet implemented):
--   [autopour]  — yield annotation: runtime pours the yielded program
--   .definition — built-in field: returns a cell's definition as text
--
-- The key insight: eval IS pour. A cell that yields a program IS
-- an evaluator. The runtime does the rest.

-- ============================================================
-- PART 1: The Universal Evaluator
--
-- Accept a program as text, yield it for autopour.
-- That's it. That's eval.
-- ============================================================

cell request
  yield program_name
  yield program_text
  ---
  This is a pour-request. Another cell or an external agent fills in
  the program name and the raw .cell text of the program to evaluate.

  Yield program_name = the name for the new program.
  Yield program_text = the complete .cell source to be poured.
  ---
  check program_text is not empty
  check program_name is not empty

cell evaluator
  given request.program_text
  given request.program_name
  yield evaluated [autopour]
  yield name
  ---
  The universal evaluator. Take «program_text» and yield it as a
  program for autopour. The runtime will parse it, verify its effect
  level, and pour it into the retort.

  If the text doesn't parse, this yield becomes bottom (error).
  If the effect level exceeds the bound, this yield becomes bottom.
  Otherwise, the program enters the retort and starts evaluating.

  Yield evaluated = «program_text»
  Yield name = «program_name»
  ---
  check evaluated is not empty

-- ============================================================
-- PART 2: Observing Results
--
-- Once a program is poured, its cells evaluate normally via the
-- runtime. We can observe the results through cross-program givens.
-- ============================================================

cell status
  given evaluator.name
  yield state
  ---
  sql: SELECT
    CASE
      WHEN COUNT(*) = 0 THEN 'not_found'
      WHEN COUNT(CASE WHEN state = 'bottom' THEN 1 END) > 0 THEN 'error'
      WHEN COUNT(CASE WHEN state != 'frozen' THEN 1 END) = 0 THEN 'complete'
      ELSE 'running'
    END AS program_state
  FROM cells
  WHERE program_id = CONCAT('', '«name»')
  ---

-- ============================================================
-- PART 3: The Self-Evaluation Question
--
-- Can this evaluator evaluate itself?
--
-- If request.program_text contains the text of THIS program
-- (cell-zero-autopour), then:
--
-- 1. evaluator receives its own source
-- 2. evaluator yields it with [autopour]
-- 3. Runtime pours a copy (cell-zero-autopour-copy)
-- 4. The copy's request cell needs program_text — from where?
-- 5. Nobody provides it → the copy's request cell sits unsatisfied
-- 6. The copy is inert. Self-evaluation terminates naturally.
--
-- This is CORRECT. The self-application of eval to eval produces
-- an inert copy. It doesn't diverge because the poured copy has
-- an unsatisfied dependency. No fuel needed for this case.
--
-- The fuel bound matters for CHAINED autopour:
-- Program A autopours Program B which autopours Program C...
-- Each pour decrements fuel. At fuel=0, autopour yields bottom.
-- ============================================================

-- ============================================================
-- PART 4: The Perpetual Evaluator (stem version)
--
-- A stem cell that continuously accepts pour-requests and evaluates
-- them. This replaces the self-spawning pattern in cell-zero-eval.
-- ============================================================

cell perpetual-request (stem)
  yield program_name
  yield program_text
  ---
  Poll for a pending pour-request. This is a stem cell — it runs
  forever, checking each generation for new work.

  sql: SELECT
    COALESCE(
      (SELECT value_text FROM yields WHERE cell_id IN
        (SELECT id FROM cells WHERE program_id = 'cell-zero-autopour'
         AND name = 'external-request' AND state = 'declared')
       AND field_name = 'text' LIMIT 1),
      ''
    ) AS program_text
  ---

cell perpetual-evaluator (stem)
  given perpetual-request.program_text
  given perpetual-request.program_name
  yield poured [autopour]
  ---
  If «program_text» is not empty, yield it for autopour.
  If empty, yield nothing (quiescent — no work this generation).

  This is the perpetual metacircular evaluator:
  a stem cell that continuously pours programs as they arrive.
  ---

-- ============================================================
-- DESIGN NOTES
--
-- What's different from cell-zero-eval.cell:
--
-- 1. NO SQL INSERTs for pouring. The [autopour] annotation tells
--    the runtime to pour. The cell yields text, not SQL.
--
-- 2. NO SQL manipulation for claiming/evaluating. The poured
--    program's cells are evaluated by the NORMAL runtime loop.
--    The evaluator doesn't need to claim or dispatch.
--
-- 3. NO self-spawning. Stem cells handle perpetuation natively.
--    No need to INSERT INTO cells to create a successor.
--
-- 4. NO reflection. The evaluator never reads from the cells
--    table or manipulates yields directly. It operates entirely
--    within the Cell language abstraction.
--
-- What's the same:
--
-- 1. Both achieve the same result: programs poured and evaluated.
-- 2. Both are perpetual (stem cells / self-spawning).
-- 3. Both handle quiescence (no work → idle).
--
-- What this proves:
--
-- With [autopour] and stem cells, the Cell language CAN express
-- its own evaluator without leaving the abstraction. This is
-- Sussman's criterion: "A language that can express its own
-- evaluator in itself is a language that can be extended by its
-- users without modifying the implementation."
--
-- The SQL in status cell is a hard computed cell — it's WITHIN
-- the language (hard cells can run SQL). The SQL in cell-zero-eval
-- was in soft cell bodies — it was the PISTON running SQL, which
-- is OUTSIDE the language.
-- ============================================================
